s3.name: Simple Storage Service (S3)
s3.description: Store and retrieve any amount of data from anywhere

s3-buckets.name: Buckets
s3-buckets.description: Buckets are containers for data stored in S3

s3-access_grants.name: S3 Access Grants
s3-access_grants.description: Control access to data sets within S3 by using identities from your corporate directory or AWS Identity and Access Management (IAM). You can create only one Access Grants instance per AWS Region per account.

s3-access_points.name: S3 Access Points
s3-access_points.description: Amazon S3 Access Points simplify managing data access at scale for shared datasets in S3. Access points are named network endpoints that are attached to buckets that you can use to perform S3 object operations. An Access Point alias provides the same functionality as an Access Point ARN and can be substituted for use anywhere an S3 bucket name is normally used for data access.

s3-object_lambda_access_points.name: Object Lambda Access Points
s3-object_lambda_access_points.description: You can use Amazon S3 Object Lambda Access Points to run custom transformations when retrieving objects.

s3-multi_region_access_points.name: Multi-Region Access Points
s3-multi_region_access_points.description: Multi-Region Access Points offer a global S3 hostname that provides access to multiple S3 buckets across AWS Regions with automatic routing and failover between buckets.

s3-batch_operations.name: Batch Operations
s3-batch_operations.description: A job is used to execute batch operations on a list of S3 objects.

s3-iam_access_analyzer.name: IAM Access Analyzer for S3
s3-iam_access_analyzer.description: The buckets listed below are configured to allow access by anyone using the internet or authenticated AWS users, including AWS users outside of your organization.

s3-block_public_access_settings_for_this.name: Block Public Access settings for this account
s3-block_public_access_settings_for_this.description: Use Amazon S3 Block public access settings to control the settings that allow public access to your data.

s3-storage_lens_dashboard.name: Storage Lens Dashboard
s3-storage_lens_dashboard.description: Storage Lens provides visibility into storage usage and activity trends at the organization or account level, with drill-downs such as AWS Region, Storage Lens groups, or prefixes.

s3-storage_lens_groups.name: Storage Lens groups
s3-storage_lens_groups.description: You can use Storage Lens groups to analyze your storage allocation and usage for large shared buckets, such as data lakes.

s3-aws_organizations_settings_for_storag.name: AWS Organizations settings for Storage Lens
s3-aws_organizations_settings_for_storag.description: You can authorize Storage Lens to access your organization hierarchy. You can also register member accounts to act as delegated administrators.

iam.name: Identity and Access Management (IAM)
iam.description: Manage User Access and Encryption Keys

iam-roles.name: Roles
iam-roles.description: An IAM role is an identity you can create that has specific permissions with credentials that are valid for short durations. Roles can be assumed by entities that you trust.

iam-policies.name: Policies
iam-policies.description: A policy is an object in AWS that defines permissions.

iam-users.name: Users
iam-users.description: An IAM user is an identity with long-term credentials that is used to interact with AWS in an account.

iam-user_groups.name: User groups
iam-user_groups.description: A user group is a collection of IAM users. Use groups to specify permissions for a collection of users.

iam-identity_providers.name: Identity providers
iam-identity_providers.description: Use an identity provider (IdP) to manage your user identities outside of AWS, but grant the user identities permissions to use AWS resources in your account.

iam-account_settings.name: Account settings
iam-account_settings.description: Use the Account settings page to configure password requirements for IAM users, create temporary credentials for trusted users using AWS Security Token Service, and turn on endpoints from which you can request temporary credentials.

iam-credential_report.name: Credential report
iam-credential_report.description: The credentials report lists all your IAM users in this account and the status of their various credentials. After a report is created, it is stored for up to four hours.

iam-scps.name: Service control policies (SCPs)
iam-scps.description: A service control policy (SCP) limits permissions for entities in member accounts in AWS Organizations.

glue.name: Glue
glue.description: fully managed ETL (extract, transform, and load) service

glue-databases.name: Databases
glue-databases.description: A database is a set of associated table definitions, organized into a logical group.

glue-tables.name: Tables
glue-tables.description: A table is the metadata definition that represents your data, including its schema. A table can be used as a source or target in a job definition.

glue-crawlers.name: Crawlers
glue-crawlers.description: A crawler connects to a data store, progresses through a prioritized list of classifiers to determine the schema for your data, and then creates metadata tables in your data catalog.

glue-jobs.name: Jobs
glue-jobs.description: This section lists all the extract, transform, and load (ETL) jobs that have been created in your account.

glue-classifiers.name: Classifiers
glue-classifiers.description: Classifiers are triggered during a crawl task. A classifier checks whether a given file is in a format the crawler can handle. If it is, the classifier creates a schema in the form of a StructType object that matches that data format.

glue-schemas.name: Schemas
glue-schemas.description: A schema is a versioned specification for reliable data exchanges across heterogeneous systems.

glue-triggers.name: Triggers
glue-triggers.description: A trigger starts a job when it fires.

glue-workflows.name: Workflows
glue-workflows.description: A workflow is an orchestration used to visualize and manage the relationship and execution of multiple triggers, jobs and crawlers.

glue-blueprints.name: Blueprints
glue-blueprints.description: A blueprint is used to generate AWS Glue workflows for common ETL use cases in your organization.

glue-data_connections.name: Data connections

glue-data_catalog_settings.name: Data catalog settings

glue-stream_schema_registries.name: Stream schema registries
glue-stream_schema_registries.description: A registry is a logical container of schemas, and schemas can only exist in a single registry.
